                article_id: "f4a8c426d6b75e28f54e970dd3e65000",
                title: "Liam Payne’s BBC boyband documentary could be delayed after his death",
                "link": "https://www.dailystar.co.uk/tv/liam-paynes-bbc-boyband-documentary-33934255",

                "description": "Liam Payne was working on a number of television projects before his untimely death this week - and two major TV shows could now be in doubt following the tragedy",
                "content": "In a shocking turn of events, two major TV shows are now reportedly \"hanging in the balance\" following the tragic demise of in Argentina. The 31 year old heartthrob and sensation met his balcony at the CasaSur Hotel in Buenos Aires on Wednesday. Insiders have hinted that it could take anywhere from 10 to 15 days for his remains to be sent back to the UK. Before his heartbreaking exit, Liam was said to be knee-deep in telly work, including a gig on an programme. He was also tied to a documentary about boybands, but with his sudden passing, the fate of these ventures is now up in the air. Liam's recent stint as a judge on 's Building The Band, where he was on the hunt for the next big boyband, had fans buzzing. Spotted in Manchester this August, where try-outs were being captured on camera, the show was tipped by The Sun to hit Netflix screens next year. However, following the star's death, its future is now cast in doubt, with Netflix keeping mum on the matter for now, reports . Another potential casualty of the tragedy is the heavyweight docuseries Boybands Forever, a collaboration with Louis Theroux. This series delves into the highs and lows of boyband life, featuring the likes of One Direction, and includes dishing out behind-the-scenes tales of the band's formation. The programme is set to hit screens next month, but following the tragic news of Liam's passing, the Beeb might delay its release. Louis spilled the beans on the show, saying: \"It involves some of the icons of modern British pop - and we see them through their highs and lows.\" He went on to reveal: \"It's how they came together, the experience of sudden fame, the opportunity and temptations that came their way, conflicts within the groups, between the groups, and between the boys and their managers.\" \"It's a gripping fable about getting everything you dreamed of, and it not being what you imagined, centred on a generation of young men, and their managers, who were wildly successful and also immensely vulnerable, having the times of their lives and also in some cases cracking up.\" The Sun has also revealed that Liam and his squad were hashing out a deal for a behind-the-scenes doc about his post-1D life, but sadly, it didn't come off. In the wake of the sad event, insiders have shared that Liam's body will probably stay in Argentina for 10 to 15 days while they wait for the toxicology test results. When the probe wraps up, the singer's remains will be released to his family and flown back to England, as per reports from Argentina's press. This would translate to the possibility of laying down the funeral plans for early next month, following the return of the body to UK shores.",
